    "type": "targeted_grid",
    "name": "targeted_sweep10c_liveness_penalty",
    "description": "Rerun of targeted_sweep10b with --enable-liveness-penalty (Option B price oracle).\nsweep10b (baseline oracle, liveness penalty OFF) found all 5 scenarios v27_dominant including econ=0.35, with econ=0.35-0.70 producing statistically identical outcomes. The retarget mechanism dominated: the 50% difficulty drop at t\u22488,122s pushed all v26 pools past their max_loss_pct threshold regardless of economic_split.\nHypothesis for this run (liveness penalty ON):\n  The liveness penalty dampens the economic factor of slower-producing chains:\n    effective_econ_f = 1.0 + (economic_factor - 1.0) * (block_rate_ratio ^ exponent)\n  During the long race phase, v26 runs at ~35.9% hashrate \u2192 block_rate_ratio \u2248 0.359,\n  further suppressing its economic factor on top of its 30-65% custody disadvantage.\n  This accelerates price divergence, potentially pushing v26-committed pools past their\n  loss threshold VIA PRICE SIGNAL ALONE \u2014 before the retarget fires.\n\nIf the hypothesis holds:\n  - Higher econ splits (0.70, 0.82) may cascade EARLIER (price-driven, not retarget-driven)\n  - Lower econ splits (0.35, 0.50) may still require the retarget, or may produce contested\n  - The \"identical outcomes\" pattern from sweep10b would break \u2014 econ_split would matter again\n\nDirect comparison to sweep10b isolates the Option B effect:\n  All parameters identical, only --enable-liveness-penalty differs.\n\nIMPORTANT: Run with --retarget-interval 2016 --duration 13000 --enable-liveness-penalty.\n",
